ce:section.ce:para:
A self-assembly method was utilized for the synthesis of the targeted catalyst C-PIL-POM-SiO2, involving the incorporation of C-dots into PIL-POM-immobilized SiO2 (Scheme 1
                        ). Fig. 1
                        a shows the XRD patterns of the prepared catalysts to characterize their crystal structures. The weak broad amorphous diffraction peaks in the range of 15-40° can be observed in the PIL-POM catalyst, indicating the characteristics of an amorphous carbon material structure. After the introduction of SiO2 and C-dots, no obvious diffraction peaks engendered or deviated in the PIL-POM-SiO2, C-PIL-POM, and C-PIL-POM-SiO2 catalysts, indicating that the uniformly dispersed C-dots did not disrupt the basic structures of the PIL-POM. The successful introduction of the C-dots was further demonstrated by FT-IR analysis (Fig. 1b). The characteristic peaks in the interval of 1100 to 750 cm−1 are ascribed to the Keggin structure of HPW, indicating the successful immobilization of HPW on the surface of PIL through non-covalent bonding (Figs. S1 and S2). For the sample PIL-POM-SiO2, the appearance of a broader absorption peak at 1085 cm−1 suggests the successful introduction of SiO2. In addition, the intensity of two absorption peaks at 1008 and 808 cm−1 remarkably increases in the PIL-POM-SiO2, which are respectively attributed to the overlap of the Si-O-Si contraction vibrations with ν(P-Oa) and ν(W-Oc-W) [51]. The peaks centered at 2950 and 2850 cm−1 correspond to the CH bond stretching vibrations of the cationic alkyl chain in the PIL. Moreover, the characteristic peaks near 1546 and 1454 cm−1 are respectively assigned to the CC and CN vibrations of imidazolium ring, further confirming the successful fabrication of the PIL-POM-SiO2 catalyst. For C-PIL-POM-SiO2 catalyst, a characteristic peak at 1654 cm−1 is assigned to the functional group carbonyl (CO) of C-dots, which overlaps with the characteristic peak of CN in the imidazole ring.
